havior, suggesting that youths do apply some sort of cost/benefit calculation when making decisions; the macroeconomic environment in which those decisions are made matters greatly; and youths who pursue high-risk behaviors are significantly more likely to engage in similar behaviors as adults. This important volume provides both a key data source for public policy makers and a clear affirmation of the usefulness of economic analysis to our understanding of risky behavior.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aDecision making in adolescencexEconomic aspectsvCongresses. 0aRisk-taking (Psychology) in adolescencexEconomic aspectsvCongresses. 0aYouthxPsychologyxEconomic aspectsvCongresses. 7aFAMILY & RELATIONSHIPS / General.2bisacsh  abehavior, youth, high school dropout rates, risk, eating disorders, nutrition, safety, life choices, suicide, mental health, depression, teenage, performance, economics, statistics, crime, unprotected sex, drug use, smoking, drinking and driving, teen, dui, psychology, adolescence, decision making, marijuana, birth control, sexual activity, juvenile, enrollment, malnourished, nonfiction, sociology.1 aBhattacharya, Jay, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCard, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChaloupka, Frank J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCook, Philip J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCurrie, Janet, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCutler, David M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDee, Thomas S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEvans, William N., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFarrelly, Ma